{"metadata":{"title":"Amherst College Press","numberOfItems":49,"itemsPerPage":50,"currentPage":1},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/api/opds/amherst?currentPage=1","type":"application/opds+json"},{"rel":"first","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/api/opds/amherst?currentPage=1","type":"application/opds+json"},{"rel":"last","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/api/opds/amherst?currentPage=1","type":"application/opds+json"}],"publications":[{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"Expressive Networks: Poetry and Platform Cultures","author":"Kilbane, Matthew","description":"\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cem\u003eExpressive Networks\u003c\/em\u003e convenes an urgent conversation on digital media and the social life of contemporary poetry. Tracing how poems circulate through online spaces and how capitalized platforms have come to pattern the reading and writing of poetry, contributors emphasize both the expressivist cast of digital literary culture and the deep-running ambivalence that characterizes aesthetic and critical responses to platformed cultural production. The volume features chapters on Pan- African spoken word programs, Singaporean Facebook groups, decolonial hemispheric networks, and Japanese media-critical poetries as well as platforms such as Twitter/X, Instagram, and Amazon.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eThough contributors write from a variety of methodological positions and address themselves to a range of archives, they share the primary conviction that the impact of Web 2.0 on literary practice is far-reaching, far from self-evident, and far more variegated and unpredictable than easy summations of social media’s influence suggest. \u003cem\u003eExpressive Networks\u003c\/em\u003e asks after poetry’s present and future by examining what poems themselves express about the social make-up of networked platforms.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eEdited by Matthew Kilbane with contributions from Cameron Awkward-Rich, Micah Bateman, Andrew Campana, Sumita Chakraborty, Scott Challener, C.R. Grimmer, Tess McNulty, Michael Nardone, Seth Perlow, Anna Preus, Susanna Sacks, Carly Schnitzler, Melanie Walsh, and Samuel Caleb Wee.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u0026quot;Online platforms matter. Poetics, poetry writing, poetry reception, poetry criticism, and all the activities that seem adjacent to those things can be shaped, remade, narrowed, or given other dimensions not just by the fact of the Internet (which is old news) or by digital composition (arguably also old news) but by the particular layered platforms on which and amid which they stand. It matters whether a poet publishes on Instagram or by hand-coding a site. It matters who pays for a spoken-word tour and who puts the tour online and how. It matters to poetic composition whether a Facebook group devoted to that composition is locked and private or open to the public. And these matters have a history: we can do literary history with them, as well as aesthetic appreciation and detraction, criticism about criticism, media-network studies, and Marxist or sorta-of-Marxist critique. All these modes of analysis turn up in \u003cem\u003eExpressive Networks\u003c\/em\u003e, and all are used well. This volume will be a big deal.\u0026quot;\u003cbr\u003e —\u003cb\u003eStephanie Burt\u003c\/b\u003e, Harvard University \u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u0026quot;This important volume offers literary criticism augmented for the age of networked platforms. From its plugged-in introduction to its well-tuned chapters, \u003cem\u003eExpressive Networks\u003c\/em\u003e offers a collection of timely readings of digital poetic objects.\u0026quot;\u003cbr\u003e —\u003cb\u003eMark Marino\u003c\/b\u003e, University of Southern California\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eMatthew Kilbane\u003c\/b\u003e is is an assistant professor in the English Department at the University of Notre Dame. A scholar of modern and contemporary poetry, media studies, and the digital humanities, he is author of \u003cem\u003eThe Lyre Book: Modern Poetic Media\u003c\/em\u003e (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2024).\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eAn auto-narrated audiobook is available via the \u0026quot;Download\u0026quot; button above.\u003c\/em\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.14525819\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.14525819","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-19T08:21:43Z","published":"2025-01-01","publisher":"Amherst College Press","subject":["Literary Studies","Poetry \u0026 Poetics","Digital \u0026 Media Studies "]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/q524jr70t/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/q524jr70t/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/5t34sp187/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/rx913s58c/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/rx913s58c/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/rx913s58c/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/rx913s58c/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"Boundless: Native American Abundance in Art and Literature","author":["Crossman, Lisa A.","Erdrich, Heid E."],"description":"\u003cdiv\u003e\u003ci\u003eBoundless\u003c\/i\u003e expands conversations on Native and Indigenous art and literature by presenting words and images in kinship. Starting in the collections of the Mead Art Museum and the Collection of Native American Literature at Amherst College and centered on the creative production of Native peoples of the Northeast, the project follows relationships between Indigenous authors and artists across the United States and beyond borders. \u003cem\u003eBoundless\u003c\/em\u003e presents an engagement of Indigenous curatorial methods as practiced by guest curator Heid E. Erdrich (Ojibwe) in an exhibition in two iterations hosted by the Mead in 2023 and 2024. Advisors to Boundless include Mohegan, Nipmuc, Shinnecock, and Wampanoag artists and scholars, along with others, who supported Erdrich in her urge to center the project in the Northeast. Advisors contributed both visual art and writing to the exhibition and publication. Collaborative co-creation between artists, students, faculty, Mead staff Lisa Crossman and Emily Potter-Ndiaye and the guest curator are also explored in this illustrated volume.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eAmherst College’s Collection of Native American Literature contains thousands of Indigenous-authored works spanning centuries. The Collection’s abundance of books, prints, music, ephemera, and artist-made works, all by Native people, provide rich selections for \u003cem\u003eBoundless\u003c\/em\u003e. Crosscurrents of Indigenous visual art and literature are considered in this broad and interdisciplinary project. \u003cem\u003eBoundless\u003c\/em\u003e crosses generations to explore relatedness, kinship, and collegiality. \u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eBoundless\u003c\/em\u003e brings artists and writers together across generations, often drawing together works by members of the same tribe or even the same family to show the history, presence, and futurity of Native American creative and intellectual production.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u0026quot;This book and exhibit establish an Indigenous sense of place. It links territory, community, aesthetics, and history. Anyone interested in poetry, art, colonization, religion, water, the environment, Massachusetts, Indigenous culture and the long history of settlement and contact in New England will be drawn to this fantastic project. Every single person who engages with \u003ci\u003eBoundless\u003c\/i\u003e will find something fascinating. It is a must read.\u0026quot;\u003cbr\u003e —\u003cb\u003eDean Rader\u003c\/b\u003e, University of San Francisco \u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eLisa A. Crossman\u003c\/b\u003e is director of curatorial affairs at the Mead Art Museum, Amherst College. Her work centers on collaborations with artists, students, faculty, and guest curators. Her current research focuses on issues related to labor.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eHeid E. Erdrich\u003c\/b\u003e (Ojibwe) is author of \u003cem\u003eLittle Big Bully\u003c\/em\u003e and many books of poetry and prose. She is an interdisciplinary artist who has curated dozens of Native arts exhibitions. Erdrich is an enrolled member of the Turtle Mountain Band of Chippewa who lives in Minnesota. Erdrich served as the 2020–2024 Amherst College Mead Museum Guest Curator.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eAn auto-narrated audiobook is available via the \u0026quot;Download\u0026quot; button above.\u003c\/em\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.14513702\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.14513702","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-19T08:22:12Z","published":"2025-01-01","publisher":"Amherst College Press","subject":["Art History \u0026 Visual Studies","Indigenous Studies"]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/nv9355980/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/nv9355980/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/n870zt66t/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//ima