lume come from fields such as anthropology, linguistics, history, sociology, and political science. Through these diverse epistemological frameworks, the authors show how people in contemporary Mexico interpret the world in racial terms and denounce racism.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eWith translations by Ellen Jones and contributions from Jumko Ogata-Aguilar, Eugenia Iturriaga, Mónica G. Moreno Figueroa, Perla Valero, Patricio Solís and Braulio Güémez, Máximo Ernesto Jaramillo-Molina, Yásnaya Elena A. Gil, Alejandra Leal, Alfonso Forssell Méndez, Itza Amanda Varela Huerta, Hugo Ceron-Anaya, Alice Krozer, José Ángel Koyoc Kú (K’ajlay), Josefa Sánchez Contreras, Meztli Yoalli Rodríguez Aguilera, Ariadna Solis, Tajëëw B. Díaz Robles\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e“This book makes a valuable contribution to the growing scholarship on racism and anti-racism in Latin America. It brings to English-speaking audiences recent work on Mexico that adds significantly to the existing literature in English; it also brings work by a diverse range of Mexican scholars and activists, early career and more established, Indigenous and non-Indigenous. It is refreshing to encounter work that really interrogates the relationship between race and class, or racism and classism, in detail and in depth using a variety of methods, including the recent quantitative work that has been done in Mexico, which is at the cutting edge of such work in Latin America and elsewhere.”\u003cbr\u003e —\u003cstrong\u003ePeter Wade\u003c\/strong\u003e, University of Manchester\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eMilena Ang\u003c\/b\u003e is assistant professor of political science at Universitat Pompeu Fabra in Barcelona. She is interested in democratization, transitional justice, and inequality in the Mexican criminal justice system. Her work has appeared in journals such as \u003ci\u003eWorld Politics\u003c\/i\u003e and \u003ci\u003eCrime, Law, and Social Change.\u003c\/i\u003e\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e